  "text": "The old ConsumerConnector interface (kafka.consumer.ConsumerConnector) from the pre-0.9 Scala-based consumer API is no longer present in this codebase\u2014it was fully removed in later Kafka versions. The modern Kafka codebase has evolved the consumer architecture into a two-implementation delegation pattern:\n\n1. **Consumer interface** (`Consumer.java`) defines the public API contract with `commitSync`/`commitAsync` methods.\n2. **KafkaConsumer** (`KafkaConsumer.java`) is the top-level facade implementing `Consumer<K,V>`, delegating to an internal `ConsumerDelegate`.\n3. **ConsumerDelegateCreator** selects between two implementations based on `group.protocol` config:\n   - **ClassicKafkaConsumer** (classic/legacy group protocol, pre-KIP-848): All network I/O on the calling thread. Uses `ConsumerCoordinator` for offset management, with `maybeAutoCommitOffsetsAsync` handling periodic auto-commits on the application thread.\n   - **AsyncKafkaConsumer** (new consumer group protocol, KIP-848): Uses an event-driven architecture with `ApplicationEventHandler` and a dedicated `ConsumerNetworkThread`. Offset commits are handled via `CommitRequestManager` which processes `SyncCommitEvent`/`AsyncCommitEvent` on the network thread.\n\nKey behavioral differences in offset management:\n- **Classic**: Auto-commit happens synchronously in `ConsumerCoordinator.maybeAutoCommitOffsetsAsync()` during `poll()` on the application thread. Offset commits are sent directly through the `ConsumerNetworkClient`.\n- **Async/New**: Auto-commit and manual commits are decoupled via events (`SyncCommitEvent`, `AsyncCommitEvent`, `CommitOnCloseEvent`). The `CommitRequestManager` on the background network thread processes these, enabling non-blocking offset management. `SubscriptionState` tracks positions and committed offsets for both implementations.",
